article.description: No. 6 LSU recovered from its first loss of the season to beat the struggling Gators 94-54 Thursday night.
article.headline: LSU bounces back from first loss to rout Florida
article.linkText: LSU bounces back from first loss to rout Florida
article.story:
GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- LSU needed just seven seconds to set the tone for its blowout win against Florida. The Tigers won the tip, and center Aiysha Smith beat everyone to the basket for a layup. A flurry of point-blank shots followed as No. 6 LSU recovered from its first loss of the season to beat the struggling Gators 94-54 Thursday night. LSU (16-1, 4-1 Southeastern Conference) took the lead for good when Smith faked an outside shot and drove straight down the lane for a layup that put the Tigers up 11-9. They put the game away with a 24-3 run midway through the first half.
“ Florida is going to win some SEC games. I just had my fingers crossed that it wouldn't start tonight. ”
— LSU coach Sue Gunter
"Florida is going to win some SEC games,'' LSU coach Sue Gunter said. "I just had my fingers crossed that it wouldn't start tonight.'' Both teams were missing a key player. Florida's leading returning scorer, center Vanessa Hayden, has been out since fracturing her left fibula Dec. 7 while LSU forward DeTrina White fractured her right foot in the Tigers' 82-72 loss to No. 8 Arkansas on Jan. 19. Forward Ke-Ke Tardy stepped in for White to score a season-high 16 points for the Tigers. Bernice Mosby led Florida (8-9, 0-5) with 14 points and 11 rebounds, and Dalila Eshe added 11 points. The Gators continued one of the worst stretches in school history, losing their fifth straight. The last four defeats have come by at least 39 points. LSU led 47-22 at halftime after shooting 61 percent in the opening half, and extended the advantage to as many as 42 points in the second half. Tardy scored 12 straight points in a span beginning at the end of the first half and stretching into the second. Florida, which had five freshmen on the floor at times, was unable to guard the Tigers inside, giving up repeated close shots off easy post-entry passes. LSU shot 58 percent from the floor. "Each team that has come in here has coaches who can sit back and let their veterans run,'' first-year Florida coach Carolyn Peck said. "I look forward to that day, and that's going to happen here.'' Smith had 15 points and reserve Roneeka Hodges added 12 for LSU.
